<FONT color=lightgoldenrod>Crusader of Justice</FONT color></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub21.ezboard.com/usirlageholyblaze.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Lage Holyblaze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/5/01 5:51:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dark Ages of Camelot</span><hr size=1> Yup the basis is that the 3 realms (Midgard, realm of the Norse -- modern day Norway etc; Hibernia -- modern day Scotland ; and Albion -- modern day England -- Camelot) go to war.  Each realm will have keeps in the frotier regions (as far away from the home cities as you can get without entering enemy territory).  These keeps will contain relics that give bonuses to the entire realm the has them; for instance, on relic gives a 10% bonus to exp for the whole realm.  Each realm starts with the same 3 relics.  <br>
<br>
As you can tell, one realm taking the other realms 10% exp bonus relic would be...well a nice bonus hehe; giving the one realm a 20% exp bonus while the other realm is down to 0% exp bonus.  There will be no interaction between realms as languages cannot be learned.  The keeps can be taken by brute force, or through strategies such as building seige equipment (catapults, rams and such) or by sending a few rogue type fellows =).  You then have to run the captured relice back to your homeland and secure the newly captured relice in a keep inside you're homelands or any keep that you have captured (you can capture keeps in other realms frontier regions.  If you hold that keep for a long enough time, the guards and the merchants that spawn there will be for your home realm, and your realms flag is flown above the keep).  You now own the enemy keep =).<br>
<br>
Game features I personally like are:<br>
<br>
1) Dynamic Questing.  You do a quest for a little boy.  You run into him 6 months later and he is a grown man at some other location.  He approaches you (not you approach him, interesting concept, no?) and gives you a quest because he knows you.  He will not for others, however.<br>
<br>
2) PvP with purpose.  Balancing in this game is crucial.  If they screw it up like Verant, they screw the whole game.  Assuming they get it right or close enough, you have epic battles to gain territory and relics.  By killing other players, you gain realm points which will eventually give you titles, increased chat abilities (like communications with multiple groups) and eventually even a trusty steed (finally, a knight can ride a horse).  There is no loss for pvp deaths.  You loose no exp and are not inconvenienced like in EQ, which brings up the next point:<br>
<br>
3) No corpse retrievals.  Repeat 10 times =).  If you die, you loose a bit of exp (you cannot loose levels) and a constitution point (stat point). You spawn back at your bind stone with all of your equipment; so when killed in PvP, you pop back with no losses at all; if ya gotta log you can do so then.  You will not loose near the exp that you loose in EQ.  I believe I heard 2 hours tops, at the highest levels.  That beats the week you can loose in EQ from a death.  But wait!  If you go back to where you died...you will have a grave.  Pray at your grave and you get 50% of your exp back.  You can essentially rez yourself.  You can also buy back the constitution point from a preist NPC (I saw someone paying a measely 82 coppers per point lost.  It should probably be more, thats pretty cheap).<br>
<br>
4) Soloing.  All PC's will be able to solo even up to level 50. A properly played level 50 PC can beat a level 50 NPC.  What a concept!  So, for those people that have busy lives, no worries about taking a ton of time to find a group, though they have a very well done group finding utility in game too.  This was also an EQ pet peeve for me; why people worked their characters up only to have them become *weaker* in relation to the environment.<br>
<br>
5) Adventure.  With the ability to solo, that means adventure!  In EQ, if you wanted to go to some dungeon that was right for your level range, or an outdoor zone, you usually had to have Verant's pet group(s).  With each class being able to solo, and a maximum group of 8 in DAoC, you can possibley take out a train of 8 NPC's your level.  That means ya won't need to muster up miltiple groups to go to a dungeon with blues anymore, or multiple groups to take a measely red or a couple of yellows.<br>
<br>
6) Graphics.  Some people like them and some think other games have better graphics (soon to be released games that is).  While graphics are not way up on the list of things that are important to me in a game, they do carry some weight.  Some of the screens I have seen of even early beta's are fantastic.  Their sky is designed so realistic that one can navigate by the sun or the stars and constellations.  The weather moves in slowly; it does not just rain...it gets cloudy...windy...foggy...and eventually rains.  They have incredible dynamic lighting.  The color of buildings and such actually change tint over the course of the day due to the location and brightness of the sun over its course from sunrise to sunset.<br>
<br>
All in all, I just can't wait.  I don't have the time I wish I had to play it much, but at least I will enjoy what time I can play it.  <br>
<br>
